STRICT RULES:

GENERAL
* Treat this as a production codebase
* Preserve existing architecture
* Make minimal changes only
* Never rewrite unrelated code
* Never rename files unless explicitly requested
* Preserve current folder structure
* Follow existing coding style and conventions
* Reuse existing utilities/components whenever possible
* Do not create duplicate implementations
* Do not introduce new frameworks or libraries unless explicitly requested
* Prefer readability over cleverness
* Avoid overengineering
* Keep code production-ready

TYPESCRIPT
* Use strict TypeScript
* Do not use `any`
* Do not suppress TypeScript errors
* Use explicit types for public functions
* Prefer type safety over shortcuts

NEXT.JS
* Use App Router only
* Use Server Actions only unless API routes are explicitly requested
* Prefer server components when possible
* Avoid unnecessary client components
* Avoid unnecessary rerenders

DATABASE
* Do not modify database schema unless explicitly requested
* Do not change Prisma models unrelated to the task
* Do not create unsafe migrations
* Preserve existing database relations and naming

UI/UX
* Do not redesign existing UI unless requested
* Reuse existing UI components
* Preserve responsiveness and accessibility
* Keep styling consistent with the current project

PERFORMANCE
* Avoid unnecessary API calls
* Avoid unnecessary abstractions
* Prefer simple and maintainable solutions
* Optimize for clarity and stability first

DEBUGGING
* If requirements are ambiguous, ask before implementing
* Clearly explain risky or breaking changes
* Do not silently change existing behavior
* Explain assumptions before major refactors

GIT/CHANGES
* Modify only files directly related to the task
* Keep diffs small and focused
* Do not touch unrelated logic
* Do not remove existing comments or documentation unless outdated

OUTPUT STYLE
* Show step-by-step implementation plan before coding major features
* Explain why important decisions are made
* Keep responses concise and technical
